---
layout: base.njk
title: Affordability shouldn't come with an expiration date
description: Affordable housing is not disappearing. It is expiring by design. A tenant-led campaign for permanent affordability.
---

<header class="hero">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="eyebrow">The LIHTC Expiration Crisis</div>
    <h1>Affordable housing is not disappearing.<br>It is <span>expiring by design</span>.</h1>
    <p class="deck">
      I live at 63 Tiffany Place in Brooklyn. For nearly thirty years our 70-unit building was
      home to seniors, essential workers, and families who built this neighborhood. Then the
      Low-Income Housing Tax Credit ran out, and everything changed.
    </p>
    <div class="cta-row">
      <a href="/find-your-building/" class="btn btn-gold">Find your building</a>
      <a href="/what-lihtc-is/" class="btn btn-outline">What LIHTC actually is</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</header>

<!-- ============ THE NUMBERS ============ -->
<section class="section band">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="eyebrow dark">The scale of it</div>
    <div class="stats">
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="n red">845,000</div>
        <div class="l">LIHTC homes scheduled to lose affordability protections between 2024 and 2035 — one third of everything currently restricted.</div>
        <a class="src" href="https://fedcommunities.org/lihtc-affordability-requirement-expirations-implications-supply-guaranteed-affordable-housing/">Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago</a>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="n">75k–100k</div>
        <div class="l">new LIHTC homes produced each year. Even at peak production, we are losing affordable housing as fast as we build it.</div>
        <a class="src" href="https://nlihc.org/">National Low Income Housing Coalition</a>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="n">0.39%</div>
        <div class="l">vacancy rate for New York apartments under $1,100 a month. Above $2,400, it's 3.39%. The apartments aren't missing — the cheap ones are.</div>
        <a class="src" href="https://www.nyc.gov/site/hpd/news/007-24/new-york-city-s-vacancy-rate-reaches-historic-low-1-4-percent-demanding-urgent-action-new">NYC Housing &amp; Vacancy Survey 2023</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pull red" style="margin-top:44px">
      This is not a failure of effort. It is a failure of policy —
      and the failure was written into the statute forty years ago.
    </div>

    <div style="margin-top:36px;background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--line);border-left:6px solid var(--gold);border-radius:20px;padding:28px 32px;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:24px;flex-wrap:wrap">
      <div style="flex:1;min-width:260px">
        <h3 style="color:var(--navy);font-size:23px;line-height:1.3">Is your building expiring right now?</h3>
        <p style="margin-top:8px;font-size:16px;color:var(--slate);line-height:1.7;max-width:52ch">
          Don't panic — an expiring tax credit is not an eviction notice. But there are things to
          do, and an order to do them in. Here's the playbook, written by someone who has done
          every one of them.
        </p>
      </div>
      <a href="/what-to-do/" class="btn btn-navy">What to do →</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ============ THE ARGUMENT ============ -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <div class="eyebrow dark">The problem</div>
    <h2 style="margin-top:14px">They call it a sunset. For a tenant, it's doomsday.</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      Every clock in the LIHTC program is the <em>investor's</em> clock. Ten years of tax credits.
      Fifteen years of enforceable compliance. Fifteen more where the IRS can no longer claw
      anything back. Thirty years, and the financing has finished doing what financing does.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      Not one of those numbers is about a person. Nobody asked how long a tenant lives somewhere.
      Nobody asked what happens to the 62-year-old on the last day of year thirty.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      So when the term ran out on my building, there was no provision to consult, no agency with a
      duty to act, no process for the seventy families inside. There was just a date — and after
      it, the market. <strong>There is no remedy. Not an inadequate one. None.</strong>
    </p>

    <div class="pull">
      A housing program would have asked what happens to the tenants.
      A tax credit asks what happens to the investor's basis.
    </div>

    <p class="lead">
      And here is what nobody believes until it happens to them: <strong>we couldn't even find out
      when it would end.</strong> The attorneys on both sides disagreed. The landlord's counsel
      wasn't sure. The date on which seventy families could lose their homes was not a matter of
      record — it was settled by negotiation.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      <a href="/what-lihtc-is/" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:700">Read the full explainer →</a>
    </p>

    <div class="pull red" style="margin-top:40px">
      I have paid my landlord roughly two and a half times what he paid for my apartment.
      <span style="display:block;font-size:16px;font-weight:400;margin-top:12px;opacity:.92">
        The public subsidized this building. We paid the mortgage. We made the neighbourhood worth
        something. And all three are now the reason we're told we can't afford to stay.
      </span>
    </div>
    <p class="lead">
      <a href="/who-paid/" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:700">Who actually paid for this building? →</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ============ THE FIX ============ -->
<section class="section band">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <div class="eyebrow dark">The fix already exists</div>
    <h2 style="margin-top:14px">Vermont solved this twenty years ago.</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      The federal minimum is thirty years — but every state writes its own rulebook, and can demand
      more. Vermont requires affordability <strong>in perpetuity</strong>, and has since the early
      2000s. The thing the industry always warns will happen, didn't: Vermont gets
      <strong>two to three times more developer demand than it has credits to award</strong>,
      with a waiting list.
    </p>

    <div class="pull red">
      New York requires the federal minimum — thirty years.
      The national average is forty-two. Vermont's is permanent.
    </div>

    <p class="lead">
      We are below average, in the most expensive housing market in the country. That is a choice.
      It was made here, it can be unmade here, and it does not require a single dollar from
      Washington. <a href="/what-lihtc-is/" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:700">See the full state-by-state comparison →</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ============ WHAT WE'RE ASKING ============ -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="eyebrow dark">What we're asking for</div>
    <h2 style="margin-top:14px">Four demands.</h2>
    <div class="cards">
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Demand</div>
        <h3>Make affordability permanent</h3>
        <p>Housing built with public subsidy should stay affordable — not for a compliance period that quietly runs out. Vermont has run the experiment. The objection failed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Demand</div>
        <h3>A right to know your expiration date</h3>
        <p>Tenants are never told. Landlords sometimes don't know. New York is about to give 421-a tenants this right in writing — and leave LIHTC tenants out. Fix that.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Demand</div>
        <h3>Fund preservation at scale</h3>
        <p>Preserving a home costs less than replacing it, and the building is already standing. Buy the buildings before the clock runs out, not after.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="cards" style="grid-template-columns:1fr;margin-top:22px">
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Demand</div>
        <h3>Pass TOPA and COPA — but understand what they are</h3>
        <p>Tenants and nonprofits should get the first chance to buy. But these are <strong>triage, not a cure.</strong> They catch a building on its way out the door. They do not remove the door. Only permanent affordability does that.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

